{
    "title": "A Passive-Aggressive Corporate Budget Denial",
    "content": "The corporation's annual budget was approved with a unanimous vote, but there was one glaring omission. The budget had been reduced by 10% due to the pandemic's economic impact on the company. However, the CEO and CFO were adamant that they could not afford to cut any further expenses. Instead, they proposed a budget reduction of 25%, which was met with stony silence from the board members. The CEO then made a bold statement, stating that the company would be able to weather the storm if only the government provided more aid. The board members looked at each other, unsure of what to do next. The CFO then proposed a budget increase of 10%, which was met with another unanimous vote. However, the CEO and CFO were not satisfied with this solution, as they believed that the company could still make it through the pandemic without any further cuts. In a last-ditch effort to save face, the CEO then proposed a budget increase of 25%, which was met with another unanimous vote. The board members looked at each other, unsure of what to do next. The CEO then made a final statement, stating that they were willing to cut any further expenses if the government would provide more aid. The board members looked at each other, unsure of what to do next. In the end, the budget was approved with a 10% reduction in expenses, but the company was left with no choice but to cut even more. The CEO and CFO were hailed as heroes for their bravery in the face of adversity, while the board members looked at each other, wondering what they had done wrong."
    ,"word_count": 100,
    "style_elements": [
        "italic",
        "bold",
        "underline"
    ]
}

